    Also the IPv4 router is considered external, not only IPv6.
    The router, ntp and dns servers may be on different machines each.
    
    * remove firewall reload step
    
    The steps above are applying the changes for the current session
    **and** are making them permanent (write to config) explicitly,
    thus there is no need to reload (load config into current session).
    
    Other possibility would be to use `firewall-cmd --permanent` option
    only to write it to config and then a `firewall-cmd --reload` at the
    end to (re-)load the new configuration.
    
